<h1>Applications of &nbsp;ppSup(ppInf())ppV(x)</h1>
<p>
The ppGloss([infinite tetrate]) has many physical applications because it is 
ppGloss([topologically conjugate]) to the ppGloss([Lambert W-function]). In other words, 
we can write an expression for the ppGloss([Lambert W-function]) in terms of the ppGloss([infinite tetrate]) as
ppTexCenter([ap-lambert-inftet], 
  [[W(x) = {}^{\infty}(\ee^{-x})x = -\ln\left( {}^{\infty}(\ee^{-x}) \right)]])
and we can write an expression for the ppGloss([infinite tetrate]) in terms of the
ppGloss([Lambert W-function]) as follows
ppTexCenter([ap-inftet-lambert], 
  [[{}^{\infty}x = \frac{W(-\ln(x))}{-\ln(x)} = \exp(-W(-\ln(x)))]])
where the second equations clearly indicate that there is a topological conjugacy between the two functions. The homeomorphism that forms the topological conjugacy between these two functions is 
ppTexInline([ap-topcnj], [[f(x) = \ee^{-x}]]) whose inverse is
ppTexInline([ap-topcnj-inv], [[f^{-1}(x) = -\ln(x)]]).
For more information, see the section on <a href="fn-tconj.html">topological conjugacy</a>.
</p>
